data.reasoningText:
Now I have a good understanding of the project structure. Let me plan the component decomposition and then implement it.

## Component Plan: Settings Dashboard

### Component Tree
```
SettingsDashboard            (page — owns active section, orchestrates layout)
├── SettingsSidebar          (vertical tab navigation)
├── ProfileSection           (profile editing form)
├── NotificationsSection     (notification preferences)
├── SecuritySection          (security settings)
│   ├── ChangePasswordPanel  (expandable password change form)
│   ├── ActiveSessionsTable  (sessions list with revoke)
└── AppearanceSection        (appearance settings with preview)


```

For the data flow, I'm thinking through whether the page should own all the data or if each section should fetch independently. Since only one section is visible at a time and they're truly independent, having the page fetch all four sections upfront would be wasteful. I'll let each section handle its own data fetching on initialization instead.

Now I'm mapping out the component structure: I need the service interface and records, then the leaf components like SettingsSidebar, ChangePasswordPanel, and ActiveSessionsTable, followed by the section containers that compose them, and finally the SettingsDashboard page that ties everything together. I'll implement these directly since I know the patterns well.

```

csharp
// Services/ISettingsService.cs
public interface ISettingsService
{
    Task<UserProfile> GetProfileAsync();
    Task UpdateProfileAsync(UserProfile profile);
    Task ChangePasswordAsync(string currentPassword, string newPassword);
    Task<List<ActiveSession>> GetActiveSessionsAsync();
    Task RevokeSessionAsync(string sessionId);
    Task<NotificationSettings> GetNotificationSettingsAsync();
    Task UpdateNotificationSettingsAsync(NotificationSettings settings);
    Task<AppearanceSettings> GetAppearanceSettingsAsync();
    Task UpdateAppearanceSettingsAsync(AppearanceSettings settings);
}

public record UserProfile(string Name, string Email, string PhoneNumber);
public record ActiveSession(string Id, string Device, DateTime LastActive);
public record NotificationSettings(bool EmailNotifications, bool PushNotifications);
public record AppearanceSettings(string Theme, string Language);
```

I'll organize everything under Components/Pages/Settings/ and start building out the components. Defining the service interface...

Now I'm sketching out the component structure, starting with the settings sidebar that'll handle navigation between different preference sections. The AppearanceSection handles theme, font, language, and layout options with a live preview area and save functionality. The SettingsDashboard page routes to /settings and manages which section displays by toggling between the sidebar and the active content area. Now I'm writing out the component implementations, starting with the dashboard page structure.

Writing component code... Continuing with the sidebar component structure...

Building the profile section layout with form inputs for user settings... Writing component logic... I need to set up the Settings directory structure and create the service implementation along with CSS isolation files for styling each component, then batch create everything efficiently while making sure to add the Services namespace to the imports.

